#!/usr/bin/env bash
# Apply the collection-driven Project (HOL-1355) and Application (HOL-1356)
# components with the local-ca CA bundle injected into each project's Quay
# Organization caBundle and each app's Quay Repository caBundle.
#
# The `project` component is the generalization of the bespoke my-project
# scaffold: it iterates the `projects` collection (holos/collections.cue) and
# renders, for every projects.<name> EXCEPT my-project (the bespoke component
# still owns it until HOL-1357), the full per-project control-plane resource set
# into clusters/k3d-holos/components/project/<name>/.  The `application` component
# iterates the `apps` collection and renders one app resource set per apps.<name>
# into clusters/k3d-holos/components/application/<app>/ (the Deployment/Service/
# HTTPRoute, the app KeycloakClient, the Quay Repository, and the Kargo
# Warehouse/Stage + Argo CD Application), each landing in its project's bare
# control namespace.  Each project's Quay Organization (and each app's Quay
# Repository) carries spec.caBundle — the per-cluster local-ca certificate the
# Holos Controller (ADR-18/ADR-19) needs to trust the in-cluster Quay registry's
# mkcert-signed serving certificate.  That trust material is per-cluster and is
# NEVER committed (it is absent from the rendered holos/deploy/ tree); it is
# injected here at apply time via the ca_bundle_pem CUE tag, the same --inject
# pattern scripts/apply-my-project and scripts/publish use.
#
# This script is the generic sibling of scripts/apply-my-project (which stays
# bespoke and is removed with the my-project component in HOL-1357).  It mirrors
# that script's posture exactly — context pinning, the CRD preflight, the
# local-ca PEM resolution, the namespace-first / RBAC-pre-apply / stale-Job
# delete ordering, and the per-resource Ready gates — but loops over every
# rendered project subdirectory instead of the single my-project component.
#
# With only my-project registered today the `project` component renders no
# output, so this script is a clean no-op (it reports "no project components
# rendered" and exits 0).  Register a real project (a projects/<name>.cue
# one-liner) and it provisions that project's control plane.
#
# ORDERING — the same prerequisites as scripts/apply-my-project:
#   1. scripts/local-ca (the local CA whose certificate is injected).
#   2. scripts/apply-svc-quay-resource-controller-creds (the holos-controller-quay-creds
#      Secret the controller authenticates to Quay with) and the Keycloak
#      controller credential — see docs/runbooks/holos-controller.md.
#   3. The master scripts/apply (the Argo CD / Kargo controllers + namespaces
#      component) and `make controller-deploy` (the Holos Controller + its CRDs).
#
# Environment overrides (identical to scripts/apply-my-project):
#   KUBE_CONTEXT     — kubectl context to apply to (default: current, must be k3d-holos).
#   CA_BUNDLE_PEM    — the local-ca certificate PEM to inject (default: read from
#                      the cert-manager/local-ca Secret, falling back to mkcert).
#   ROLLOUT_TIMEOUT  — per-gate timeout (default: 300s).
#   KEEP_WORKDIR     — keep the temporary render directory for debugging.

set -euo pipefail

SCRIPT_DIR="$(cd "$(dirname "${BASH_SOURCE[0]}")" && pwd)"
REPO_ROOT="$(cd "${SCRIPT_DIR}/.." && pwd)"
HOLOS_DIR="${REPO_ROOT}/holos"

ROLLOUT_TIMEOUT="${ROLLOUT_TIMEOUT:-300s}"

# Convert a kubectl-style duration to whole seconds (same grammar as
# scripts/apply-my-project's duration_seconds).
duration_seconds() {
  local duration="$1" rest="$1" total=0
  if [[ ! "${duration}" =~ ^([0-9]+[hms])+$ ]]; then
    echo "ERROR: cannot parse duration '${duration}' (expected e.g. 300s, 5m, 1h30m)." >&2
    return 1
  fi
  while [[ "${rest}" =~ ^([0-9]+)([hms]) ]]; do
    case "${BASH_REMATCH[2]}" in
      h) total=$((total + 10#${BASH_REMATCH[1]} * 3600)) ;;
      m) total=$((total + 10#${BASH_REMATCH[1]} * 60)) ;;
      s) total=$((total + 10#${BASH_REMATCH[1]})) ;;
    esac
    rest="${rest:${#BASH_REMATCH[0]}}"
  done
  echo "${total}"
}

ROLLOUT_TIMEOUT_SECONDS="$(duration_seconds "${ROLLOUT_TIMEOUT}")" || exit 1

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Prerequisites
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
missing=0
for tool in holos kubectl; do
  if ! command -v "${tool}" >/dev/null 2>&1; then
    echo "ERROR: '${tool}' not found on PATH." >&2
    [[ "${tool}" == holos ]] && echo "       Install from https://holos.run/docs/cli/" >&2
    missing=1
  fi
done
if [[ "${missing}" -ne 0 ]]; then
  exit 1
fi

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Resolve and pin the target context (the scripts/apply posture)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
if [[ -z "${KUBE_CONTEXT:-}" ]]; then
  KUBE_CONTEXT="$(kubectl config current-context)"
  if [[ "${KUBE_CONTEXT}" != "k3d-holos" ]]; then
    echo "ERROR: current kubectl context is '${KUBE_CONTEXT}', expected 'k3d-holos'." >&2
    echo "       The rendered manifests target the k3d-holos cluster.  Set" >&2
    echo "       KUBE_CONTEXT explicitly to apply to a different context." >&2
    exit 1
  fi
fi
echo "Will apply manifests to kubectl context: ${KUBE_CONTEXT}"

if ! kubectl --context "${KUBE_CONTEXT}" version --request-timeout=10s >/dev/null 2>&1; then
  echo "ERROR: cannot reach the cluster for kubectl context '${KUBE_CONTEXT}'." >&2
  echo "       Create the local cluster with scripts/local-k3d (see docs/local-cluster.md)." >&2
  exit 1
fi

# Preflight: the Holos Controller's Organization CRD must be installed, or the
# component apply below fails with `no matches for kind "Organization"`.
if ! kubectl --context "${KUBE_CONTEXT}" get crd organizations.quay.holos.run \
  --request-timeout=10s >/dev/null 2>&1; then
  echo "ERROR: the organizations.quay.holos.run CRD is not installed on context '${KUBE_CONTEXT}'." >&2
  echo "       The Holos Controller reconciles each project's Organization; install it first with:" >&2
  echo "         make controller-deploy" >&2
  echo "       (see docs/runbooks/holos-controller.md).  scripts/apply does not install the controller." >&2
  exit 1
fi

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Resolve the local-ca PEM to inject as each Organization's caBundle
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
CA_BUNDLE_PEM="${CA_BUNDLE_PEM:-}"
if [[ -z "${CA_BUNDLE_PEM}" ]]; then
  echo "Reading the local-ca Secret from cert-manager in context ${KUBE_CONTEXT} ..." >&2
  CA_BUNDLE_PEM="$(kubectl --context "${KUBE_CONTEXT}" --namespace cert-manager \
    get secret local-ca -o jsonpath='{.data.ca\.crt}' 2>/dev/null | base64 -d || true)"
fi
if [[ -z "${CA_BUNDLE_PEM}" ]] && command -v mkcert >/dev/null 2>&1; then
  caroot="$(mkcert -CAROOT 2>/dev/null || true)"
  if [[ -n "${caroot}" && -f "${caroot}/rootCA.pem" ]]; then
    echo "local-ca Secret unreadable; falling back to ${caroot}/rootCA.pem" >&2
    CA_BUNDLE_PEM="$(cat "${caroot}/rootCA.pem")"
  fi
fi
if [[ -z "${CA_BUNDLE_PEM}" ]]; then
  echo "ERROR: could not resolve the local-ca PEM." >&2
  echo "       Run scripts/local-ca first, or set CA_BUNDLE_PEM to the local CA certificate." >&2
  exit 1
fi

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Render the platform with the local-ca PEM injected (cleaned up on exit)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
WORKDIR="$(mktemp -d "${HOLOS_DIR}/.apply-projects.XXXXXX")"
RENDER_DIR="${WORKDIR}/deploy"
cleanup() {
  if [[ -z "${KEEP_WORKDIR:-}" ]]; then
    rm -rf "${WORKDIR}"
  else
    echo "KEEP_WORKDIR set; left render directory at ${WORKDIR}" >&2
  fi
}
trap cleanup EXIT
trap 'exit 130' INT
trap 'exit 143' TERM

echo "Rendering platform with ca_bundle_pem injected ..." >&2
(
  cd "${HOLOS_DIR}"
  holos render platform \
    --inject "ca_bundle_pem=${CA_BUNDLE_PEM}" \
    --write-to "$(basename "${WORKDIR}")/deploy"
) >&2

PROJECT_BASE="${RENDER_DIR}/clusters/k3d-holos/components/project"
APPLICATION_BASE="${RENDER_DIR}/clusters/k3d-holos/components/application"
NAMESPACE_DIR="${RENDER_DIR}/clusters/k3d-holos/components/namespaces"
KEYCLOAK_INSTANCE_DIR="${RENDER_DIR}/clusters/k3d-holos/components/keycloak-instance"

have_dir() { [[ -d "$1" ]] && [[ -n "$(ls -A "$1" 2>/dev/null)" ]]; }

# Nothing to do if NEITHER the generic project component NOR the application
# component rendered anything (the generic project component skips my-project,
# and an app may be attached to my-project — applied by scripts/apply-my-project,
# not here — so the project base can be empty while applications still render,
# and vice versa).  Either alone is enough to proceed.
if ! have_dir "${PROJECT_BASE}" && ! have_dir "${APPLICATION_BASE}"; then
  echo "No project or application components rendered (the generic project component" >&2
  echo "skips my-project, and no other project or app is registered).  Nothing to apply." >&2
  exit 0
fi

if [[ ! -d "${KEYCLOAK_INSTANCE_DIR}" ]]; then
  echo "ERROR: render produced no keycloak-instance manifests under ${RENDER_DIR}." >&2
  exit 1
fi

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Apply the central KeycloakInstance + ReferenceGrant (shared by all projects)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# The KeycloakInstance carries the injected local-ca caBundle and the
# ReferenceGrant authorizes each project namespace's Keycloak CRs to reference
# it.  Applied once before any project component, from this injected render (the
# committed tree omits the caBundle), exactly as scripts/apply-my-project does.
echo "==> keycloak-instance" >&2
kubectl --context "${KUBE_CONTEXT}" apply --server-side --force-conflicts \
  -f "${KEYCLOAK_INSTANCE_DIR}/"

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Gate helpers (lifted from scripts/apply-my-project)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
gate_job() {
  local namespace="$1" job="job/$2"
  local job_state lookup_failures=0
  local deadline=$((SECONDS + ROLLOUT_TIMEOUT_SECONDS))
  while true; do
    if job_state=$(kubectl --context "${KUBE_CONTEXT}" --namespace "${namespace}" \
      get "${job}" --ignore-not-found --request-timeout=10s \
      -o jsonpath='{.metadata.name}{"\n"}{range .status.conditions[*]}{.type}={.status}{"\n"}{end}'); then
      lookup_failures=0
      if [[ -z "${job_state}" ]] || grep -q '^Complete=True$' <<<"${job_state}"; then
        break
      fi
      if grep -q '^Failed=True$' <<<"${job_state}"; then
        echo "ERROR: ${namespace}/${job} failed; inspect it with:" >&2
        echo "       kubectl --context ${KUBE_CONTEXT} --namespace ${namespace} describe ${job}" >&2
        return 1
      fi
    else
      lookup_failures=$((lookup_failures + 1))
      if ((lookup_failures >= 3)); then
        echo "ERROR: cannot query ${namespace}/${job}: ${lookup_failures} consecutive lookup failures." >&2
        return 1
      fi
    fi
    if ((SECONDS >= deadline)); then
      echo "ERROR: timed out after ${ROLLOUT_TIMEOUT} waiting for ${namespace}/${job} to complete." >&2
      return 1
    fi
    sleep 5
  done
}

gate_ready() {
  # gate_ready NAMESPACE RESOURCE [TERMINAL_READY_REASON_REGEX]: poll a holos.run
  # resource to Ready=True, tolerating absence (apply lag) and failing fast on a
  # terminal failure.  NAMESPACE empty → cluster-scoped (no --namespace).
  #
  # The jsonpath emits EVERY status condition as a "<type>=<status>=<reason>" line
  # (not just the Ready condition), so two distinct terminal signals are
  # detectable: (1) the Ready condition reporting False with a reason in the
  # TERMINAL_READY_REASON_REGEX set (e.g. Conflict|ReferenceNotGranted that a
  # retry cannot clear), and (2) a SEPARATE Stalled=True condition — Kargo's
  # Project reports adoption failure as its own Stalled condition, NOT as a
  # Ready reason, so a Ready-reason match alone would never catch it and the gate
  # would block to timeout.  Both fail the gate immediately.
  local namespace="$1" resource="$2" terminal="${3:-Conflict|ReferenceNotGranted}"
  local state lookup_failures=0
  local deadline=$((SECONDS + ROLLOUT_TIMEOUT_SECONDS))
  local ns_args=()
  [[ -n "${namespace}" ]] && ns_args=(--namespace "${namespace}")
  while true; do
    if state=$(kubectl --context "${KUBE_CONTEXT}" "${ns_args[@]}" \
      get "${resource}" --ignore-not-found --request-timeout=10s \
      -o jsonpath='{range .status.conditions[*]}{.type}={.status}={.reason}{"\n"}{end}'); then
      lookup_failures=0
      if [[ -z "${state}" ]]; then
        :
      elif grep -q '^Ready=True=' <<<"${state}"; then
        break
      elif grep -q '^Stalled=True=' <<<"${state}"; then
        echo "ERROR: ${namespace:-(cluster)}/${resource} is Stalled (often the namespace is missing the" >&2
        echo "       kargo.akuity.io/project: \"true\" adoption label); inspect it with:" >&2
        echo "       kubectl --context ${KUBE_CONTEXT} ${ns_args[*]} describe ${resource}" >&2
        return 1
      elif grep -qE "^Ready=False=(${terminal})\$" <<<"${state}"; then
        local reason; reason="$(grep '^Ready=False=' <<<"${state}" | head -1)"
        echo "ERROR: ${namespace:-(cluster)}/${resource} hit a terminal Ready=False (${reason##*=}); inspect it with:" >&2
        echo "       kubectl --context ${KUBE_CONTEXT} ${ns_args[*]} describe ${resource}" >&2
        return 1
      fi
    else
      lookup_failures=$((lookup_failures + 1))
      if ((lookup_failures >= 3)); then
        echo "ERROR: repeated failures reading ${namespace:-(cluster)}/${resource}; aborting the gate." >&2
        return 1
      fi
    fi
    if ((SECONDS >= deadline)); then
      echo "ERROR: timed out waiting for ${namespace:-(cluster)}/${resource} to become Ready; inspect it with:" >&2
      echo "       kubectl --context ${KUBE_CONTEXT} ${ns_args[*]} describe ${resource}" >&2
      return 1
    fi
    sleep 5
  done
}

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Application apply/gate helpers (HOL-1356)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# The Application component renders one subdirectory per apps.<name> entry into
# components/application/<app>/.  Every app resource (the Deployment/Service/
# HTTPRoute, the app KeycloakClient, the Quay Repository, and the Kargo
# Warehouse/Stage + Argo CD Application) lands in the app's PROJECT's bare
# control namespace — the SAME namespace the project's role KeycloakGroups live
# in, so the role groups' clientRef to the app KeycloakClient resolves
# same-namespace.  That co-location is exactly why the app resources must be
# APPLIED before the project's role groups are gated Ready: the project's role
# KeycloakGroups now carry a clientRef to each app's KeycloakClient, so the group
# reconciler marks the group NOT Ready until that app KeycloakClient exists.
# apply_application_resources is therefore split from its gate: a project's apps
# are applied right after the project (before the project's group gates), and
# gated afterward.
#
# An app's namespace is the app's `project` — read from the rendered manifests'
# metadata.namespace (== the project == the bare control namespace).

# The Application component renders each app into TWO subdirectories:
#   <app_dir>control-plane/ — the operator-applied control plane (Repository,
#     KeycloakClient, Warehouse, Stage, Argo CD Application).  This script applies
#     ONLY this subtree.
#   <app_dir>workload/       — the Deployment/Service/HTTPRoute/ConfigMap/SA/
#     RoleBinding the app's Argo CD Application SYNCS from the published
#     <app>-config artifact.  This script NEVER applies it (Argo CD owns it), so
#     it never becomes a second manager of the workload objects.

# app_namespace APP_DIR APP — echo the app's control namespace (its project),
# read from the rendered control-plane Repository's metadata.namespace.
app_namespace() {
  local app_dir="$1" app="$2"
  local repo_file="${app_dir}control-plane/repository-${app}-config.yaml"
  if [[ ! -f "${repo_file}" ]]; then
    echo "ERROR: rendered Repository manifest ${repo_file} not found for app ${app}." >&2
    return 1
  fi
  kubectl --context "${KUBE_CONTEXT}" create --dry-run=client \
    -o jsonpath='{.metadata.namespace}' -f "${repo_file}"
}

# apply_application_resources APP_DIR APP — apply ONLY the app's CONTROL-PLANE
# subdirectory (Repository, KeycloakClient, Warehouse, Stage, Argo CD
# Application), WITHOUT gating.  The WORKLOAD subdirectory is deliberately NOT
# applied: the app's Argo CD Application delivers it from the published
# <app>-config artifact, so applying it here would make this script a second
# manager fighting Argo CD's self-heal.  Until the first scripts/publish of
# <app>-config, the app's Argo CD Application is Missing/Unknown — expected
# scaffolding, exactly as the my-project Application is.  The control namespace
# must already exist (applied by the project loop, or by scripts/apply-my-project
# for a my-project app).
apply_application_resources() {
  local app_dir="$1" app="$2"
  local cp_dir="${app_dir}control-plane"
  echo "==> apply application ${app} (control plane)" >&2
  if [[ -d "${cp_dir}" ]] && [[ -n "$(ls -A "${cp_dir}" 2>/dev/null)" ]]; then
    kubectl --context "${KUBE_CONTEXT}" apply --server-side --force-conflicts -f "${cp_dir}/"
  fi
}

# gate_application APP_NS APP — gate one app's KeycloakClient and Repository
# (named <app>-config, the managed config artifact repo) to Ready.
gate_application() {
  local app_ns="$1" app="$2"
  gate_ready "${app_ns}" "keycloakclient.keycloak.holos.run/${app}" || return 1
  gate_ready "${app_ns}" "repository.quay.holos.run/${app}-config" "Conflict" || return 1
}

# The set of app subdirectories already applied inside the project loop, so the
# orphan sweep below applies only apps whose project is NOT a rendered project
# (e.g. an app attached to my-project, whose project is applied by
# scripts/apply-my-project).  Keyed by app name.
declare -A APPLIED_APPS=()

# apps_for_project PROJECT — echo the app subdirectory paths whose control
# namespace is PROJECT (i.e. apps attached to that project).  Runs inside a
# command/process substitution, so a hard failure here cannot reliably abort the
# parent shell; a malformed render that makes app_namespace fail simply yields no
# match, and the caller (or the orphan sweep) re-derives the namespace with a
# real `|| exit 1` in the main shell, surfacing the error there.
apps_for_project() {
  local project="$1" app_dir app app_ns
  have_dir "${APPLICATION_BASE}" || return 0
  for app_dir in "${APPLICATION_BASE}"/*/; do
    [[ -d "${app_dir}" ]] || continue
    app="$(basename "${app_dir}")"
    app_ns="$(app_namespace "${app_dir}" "${app}")" || continue
    [[ "${app_ns}" == "${project}" ]] && printf '%s\n' "${app_dir}"
  done
}

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Apply each rendered project (and its apps), then gate them
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
if have_dir "${PROJECT_BASE}"; then
for project_dir in "${PROJECT_BASE}"/*/; do
  [[ -d "${project_dir}" ]] || continue
  NAME="$(basename "${project_dir}")"
  # The control namespace is the bare project name (the bare-<name> control
  # namespace resolution — see holos/components/project/buildplan.cue).
  CTRL_NS="${NAME}"
  echo "================================================================" >&2
  echo "==> project ${NAME} (control namespace ${CTRL_NS})" >&2

  # Namespace first (owned by the namespaces component): the bare control
  # namespace carries the kargo.akuity.io/project adoption label the Kargo
  # Project gates on.
  ns_file="${NAMESPACE_DIR}/namespace-${CTRL_NS}.yaml"
  if [[ ! -f "${ns_file}" ]]; then
    echo "ERROR: namespace manifest ${ns_file} not found for project ${NAME}." >&2
    exit 1
  fi
  echo "==> namespace ${CTRL_NS}" >&2
  kubectl --context "${KUBE_CONTEXT}" apply --server-side --force-conflicts -f "${ns_file}"

  # Pre-apply ServiceAccounts + RBAC before the Jobs (the filename-ordering race
  # guard lifted from scripts/apply-my-project).
  rbac_files=()
  for f in "${project_dir}"serviceaccount-*.yaml \
           "${project_dir}"role-*.yaml \
           "${project_dir}"rolebinding-*.yaml; do
    [[ -e "${f}" ]] && rbac_files+=(-f "${f}")
  done
  if ((${#rbac_files[@]})); then
    kubectl --context "${KUBE_CONTEXT}" apply --server-side --force-conflicts "${rbac_files[@]}"
  fi

  # Delete the prior webhook-token bootstrap Job so each run re-runs a fresh
  # idempotent token-generate (a completed Job's pod template is immutable).
  kubectl --context "${KUBE_CONTEXT}" --namespace "${CTRL_NS}" \
    delete job -l "app.kubernetes.io/name=${NAME}-quay-webhook-bootstrap" \
    --ignore-not-found --cascade=foreground --wait --request-timeout=60s

  # Apply the full project component.
  echo "==> apply ${NAME}" >&2
  kubectl --context "${KUBE_CONTEXT}" apply --server-side --force-conflicts -f "${project_dir}"

  # Apply this project's apps BEFORE the project's role-group Ready gates: the
  # role groups carry a clientRef to each app's KeycloakClient, so they cannot go
  # Ready until that app KeycloakClient exists (else the gates below time out).
  while IFS= read -r app_dir; do
    [[ -n "${app_dir}" ]] || continue
    app="$(basename "${app_dir}")"
    apply_application_resources "${app_dir}" "${app}"
    APPLIED_APPS["${app}"]=1
  done < <(apps_for_project "${NAME}")

  # Gates: webhook Job complete, Kargo Project Ready (cluster-scoped), the Quay
  # Organization Ready, and the keycloak.holos.run resources Ready.
  gate_job "${CTRL_NS}" "${NAME}-quay-webhook-bootstrap" || exit 1
  # The cluster-scoped Kargo Project: gate_ready detects its Stalled=True
  # condition (adoption failure) directly, so no Ready-reason override is needed.
  gate_ready "" "project.kargo.akuity.io/${NAME}" || exit 1
  gate_ready "${CTRL_NS}" "organization.quay.holos.run/${NAME}" "Conflict" || exit 1
  gate_ready "${CTRL_NS}" "keycloakclient.keycloak.holos.run/${NAME}" || exit 1
  for r in owner editor viewer; do
    gate_ready "${CTRL_NS}" "keycloakgroup.keycloak.holos.run/${NAME}-roles-${r}" || exit 1
    gate_ready "${CTRL_NS}" "keycloakgroup.keycloak.holos.run/${NAME}-custodians-${r}" || exit 1
  done
  # One KeycloakUser per owner; gate each rendered user.
  for user_file in "${project_dir}"keycloakuser-*.yaml; do
    [[ -e "${user_file}" ]] || continue
    user_name="$(basename "${user_file}" .yaml)"
    user_name="${user_name#keycloakuser-}"
    gate_ready "${CTRL_NS}" "keycloakuser.keycloak.holos.run/${user_name}" || exit 1
  done

  # Now gate this project's apps (their KeycloakClient + Repository).
  while IFS= read -r app_dir; do
    [[ -n "${app_dir}" ]] || continue
    app="$(basename "${app_dir}")"
    app_ns="$(app_namespace "${app_dir}" "${app}")" || exit 1
    gate_application "${app_ns}" "${app}" || exit 1
    echo "application ${app} applied." >&2
  done < <(apps_for_project "${NAME}")

  echo "project ${NAME} applied." >&2
done
fi

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Orphan sweep: apply apps whose project is NOT a rendered project component
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# An app may be attached to a project the generic component does not render here
# (today, my-project — whose namespace and project-level CRs scripts/apply-my-project
# applies).  Its app resources still rendered under components/application/<app>/;
# apply and gate them here, against the already-existing project namespace.
if have_dir "${APPLICATION_BASE}"; then
  for app_dir in "${APPLICATION_BASE}"/*/; do
    [[ -d "${app_dir}" ]] || continue
    app="$(basename "${app_dir}")"
    [[ -n "${APPLIED_APPS[${app}]:-}" ]] && continue
    app_ns="$(app_namespace "${app_dir}" "${app}")" || exit 1
    echo "================================================================" >&2
    echo "==> application ${app} (namespace ${app_ns}) [orphan: project applied elsewhere]" >&2
    apply_application_resources "${app_dir}" "${app}"
    gate_application "${app_ns}" "${app}" || exit 1
    echo "application ${app} applied." >&2
  done
fi

echo "All rendered projects and applications applied."
